photo.description: Portion of an early parchment bifolium from a missal written in a Gothic bookhand in 2 columns frame-ruled in ink (first line of text below top line of ruling) with rubrics, 1- and 2-line initials, and capital strokes in red, 1 6-line initial T in blue and white (with additional decorative penwork in brown ink supplied by a later hand?), and a pair of stylized foliate border elements (one primarily in pink, the other primarily in green). Text visible in this image: left-hand column contains gospel reading from John 12:22-26; offertory (Ps. 95(96):6); and beginning of secret ("Accipe, quaesumus, Domine, munera dignanter oblata ..."); right-hand column contains end of secret (as above); communion (John 12:26); and postcommunion (here "Co[m]pl[e]n[dum].": "Sacro munere satiati supplices ... tuae sentiamus augmentum."), all possibly for one of the commons of martyrs, followed by the introit and oratio for the dedication of a church. Penn Libraries call number: GC5 F1125 532s All images from this book
photo.title: Portion of an early parchment bifolium from a missal written in a Gothic bookhand

photo.description: Portion of an early vellum bifolium from a missal written in a Gothic bookhand in 2 columns frame-ruled in ink (first line of text below top line of ruling) with rubrics, 1- and 2-line initials, and capital strokes in red. photo.description: Leaf A4 (recto visible) from Schatzbehalter der wahren Reichtümer des Heils by Stephan Fridolin, O.F.M., printed in Nuremberg by Anton Koberger on 8 November 1491 (ISTC is00306000). photo.description: Upper inscription: Hieronymus Sauler Eccl Mosbac: Pastor [Hieronymus Sauler (1639-1716), schoolmaster at Ansbach and pastor at Mosbach, according to this entry in the catalog of the Staats- und Universitätsbibliothek Hamburg. According to this transcription of the appendix of the Gedenck-, Stadt- und Huth-Buch (Chronik der Stadt Feuchtwangen), Sauler served as pastor of Mosbach from 1674 until his death.] Lower inscription: Theophili Pauli Christii Coburgensis [Gottlieb Paul Christ (1707-1786), professor, librarian and court functionary at Ansbach. In their finding aid Aldine Press Books at the Harry Ransom Humanities Research Center, The University of Texas at Austin (Austin: The Center, 1998), Craig W. Kallendorf and Maria X. Wells identify the ex-libris "Theophili Pauli Christi" as "Gottlieb Paul Christ (18th cent.), prof. at Anspach Gymnasium". According to his biographical entry in C.A. Baader, Lexikon Verstorbener Schrifsteller des 18. und 19. Jahrhunderts (Augsburg: Von Jenisch- und Stage'schen Buchhandlung, 1825), Bd. 2, T. 1, p. 22, Christ was born in Coburg but came to Ansbach in 1728 to take service with Freiherr von Seckendorff (probably Christoph Ludwig Freiherr von Seckendorff-Aberdar). He went abroad on several diplomatic missions and became the librarian for the Ansbacher Schlossbibliothek. (According to E.F.C. Oertel in Georg Ludwig Oeder der erste Rektor bei der Einweihung des neuen Gymnasiums in Ansbach am 12. Juni 1737 ... (Ansbach: Oertel, 1837) p. 54-55, he got the job in 1738; according to the Schlossbibliothek's history web page, he was the second librarian to be appointed.) In 1737 he was appointed professor at the gymnasium in Ansbach and published a number of works on historical subjects; he also continued to serve at court as a councillor. DNB heading: Christ, Gottlieb Paul 1707-1786] Other examples of Gottlieb Paul Christ provenance Penn Libraries call number: GC5 Eb355 550c 1559

photo.description: Lower board: one leaf of a ms. bifolium (verso visible), containing glosses on Gregory's Decretals? Most entries open with the words "Nota quod"; the red-underlined headings appear to correspond to the opening word(s) of the chapter being glossed. Frame ruling visible; text written in brown ink in 2 columns of 36 lines (first line below top line of ruling) with red rubric, initials, paragraph marks, and underlines. In the left-hand column, the visible red-underlined headings correspond to the opening words of lib. 3, tit. 4, cap. 6-13: C{onsequente} De cet[er]o Ex parte Qualit[er] Int[er] q[ua]tuor Ex tue Tue Ex p[ar]te In the right-hand column, the first heading corresponds to the title of lib. 3, tit. 4, cap. 16: "Cum ad h[oc]". The next heading, "Clericos quida[m]," probably refers to cap. 17, which begins (in this edition, at least), "Clericos in ecclesiis tuae". The rubric "De p[re]bendis et dignitatibus" corresponds to the title of lib. 3, tit. 5, and the visible red-underlined headings which follow correspond to the opening words of the text of cap. 4-9: E{piscopus} Quia i[n] tantu[m] Cum tenea[mur] Refferente [sic] Maiorib[us] Relatu[m] Penn Libraries call number: GC5 D5668 524d 1525 All images from this book
photo.title: One leaf of a ms. bifolium (verso visible), containing glosses on Gregory's Decretals?

photo.description: Upper board: one leaf of a ms. bifolium (recto visible), containing glosses on Gregory's Decretals? Most entries open with the words "Nota quod"; the red-underlined headings appear to correspond to the opening word(s) of the chapter being glossed. Frame ruling visible; text written in brown ink in 2 columns of 36 lines (first line below top line of ruling) with red initials and underlines. In the left-hand column, the red-underlined headings appear to correspond to the opening words of lib. 2, tit. 27, cap. 11-15: C{onsangu}i[n]ei Cu{m ol}im C{um inter} C{ausam q}ue int[er] Q{uod ad consultationem?} In the left-hand column, the red-underlined headings appear to correspond to the opening words of lib. 2, tit. 27, cap. 16-20: Sicut nob[is] Cum su[per] [con]tro. Cum b[er]tholdus In causis Int[er] The text following the heading "Cum b[er]tholdus" can be found in the glossa ordinaria of the Decretals, lib. 2, tit. 27, cap. 18. Penn Libraries call number: GC5 D5668 524d 1525 All images from this book

photo.description: Ex biblica. Altempsna. [Ms. ownership inscription of the Biblioteca Altempsiana. It was founded by the Austrian churchman Markus Sittikus von Hohenems, Cardinal Altemps (1531-1595), nephew of Pope Pius IV, at the Palazzo Altemps in Rome and expanded by his nephew Mark Sittich, Archbishop of Salzburg (1574-1619). (Both men are also known by the Italianized form of their name, Marco Sittico Altemps, Altemps being a calque of Hohenems.) The library was eventually absorbed into the Biblioteca vaticana.] Established heading: Biblioteca altempsiana. Penn Libraries call number: GC5 C6427 545i All images from this book

photo.description: Probably Austin Lamont (1905-1969), son of Thomas W. Lamont, banker at JP Morgan after whom Harvard's Lamont Library is named. According to this article in Anesthesiology, Austin Lamont was "originally planning to study classic Latin and Greek at the New College, Oxford University, England, [but] he changed his mind while still on the steamship headed for Europe." He instead studied science and became a doctor and professor of anesthesiology at the University of Pennsylvania School of Medicine (1947-mid1960s). Austin and his 2nd wife Bodine were Philadelphia elites and associated with other prominent Philadelphians Carl and Laura Zigrosser. Carl Zigrosser was a prints curator at the Philadelphia Museum of Art and member of the Print Club (Philadelphia). A finding aid to Zigrosser's papers is available here. Other examples of Austin Lamont's autograph. Penn Libraries call numbers: LatC M2484.3 1528 All images from this book LatC Qu457.2 1514 LatC Se562.21 1522
photo.title: Austin Lamont (1905-1969)

photo.description: Bookplate: H. C. Hollway-Calthrop dated: Florence Dec. 1883 Inscription: A. Lamont Probably Austin Lamont (1905-1969), son of Thomas W. Lamont, banker at JP Morgan after whom Harvard's Lamont Library is named. According to this article in Anesthesiology, Austin Lamont was "originally planning to study classic Latin and Greek at the New College, Oxford University, England, [but] he changed his mind while still on the steamship headed for Europe." He instead studied science and became a doctor and professor of anesthesiology at the University of Pennsylvania School of Medicine (1947-mid1960s). Austin and his 2nd wife Bodine were Philadelphia elites and associated with other prominent Philadelphians Carl and Laura Zigrosser. Carl Zigrosser was a prints curator at the Philadelphia Museum of Art and member of the Print Club (Philadelphia). A finding aid to Zigrosser's papers is available here. Other examples of Austin Lamont's autograph. Penn Libraries call number: LatC L7649 518d

photo.description: Inscription at head: H: Pfau Winterthur [The Pfau (="peacock") family of Wintherthur, Switzerland, were notable 17th- and early 18th-century potters, oven-makers and -painters. Five of its members active in their craft were named Hans Heinrich: Hans Heinrich I (1559-1636), Hans Heinrich II (1598-1673), Hans Heinrich III (1642-1719), Hans Heinrich IV (1672-1714), and Hans Heinrich V (fl. 1702-1740?). Cf. their entries in Schweizerisches Künsterlexikon (Frauenfeld: Huber & Co., 1905-1917), 2. Bd., p. 539f; cf. also the entry for the Pfau family in the online SIKART Lexikon und Datenbank zur Kunst in der Schweiz und im Fürstentum Liechtenstein.] Inscription at foot: nunc Davidis Sulzeri. 1706. ["Der beste Winterthurer Ofenmaler des 18. Jahrhunderts war David Sulzer (1716-1792). Er weist in reiner Blumenmalerei, in stilisiertem Blumenornament, in kleinen Landschaften auf Wege, die den ausschliesslichen Ofenschmuck seit der Mitte des 18. Jahrhunderts ausmachen sollten." -- M. Lüthi, Bürgerliche Innendekoration des Spätbarock und Rokoko in der deutschen Schweiz (Zürich: Art. Institut Orell Füssli, 1927), p. 43 (citing an article by a Dr. Hafner in Winterthurer Neujahrsblatt 1876). Sulzer is also mentioned in A. Jacquemart, History of the Ceramic Art, tr. B. Palliser (London: Sampson Low et al., 1873), p. 490, and an example of his work in collaboration with potter Ottmar Vogler of Elgg is briefly described in B. Bucher, ed., Geschichte der Technischen Künste, 3. Bd. photo.description: First inscription: Sum ex libris Ioan: Kaufmannj Vitodurani emptis ab haeredibus Matthiae Cellarij. Ano. 1539. [...]: 1439. M. Cellarius. [Ownership inscription of Joannes Kaufmannus of Winterthur, noting that this volume was purchased from the heirs of Matthias Cellarius (d. 1586; enrolled Universität Basel 1575/1576; pastor of Seuzach, Switzerland, near Winterthur, 1580-1586). The "Ano. 1539" is probably an attempt to supply a date to the imprint; at the end of the preface, the date "MDXLI" (1541) has been crossed out and replaced in ms. with "1539". A later hand appears to have interpreted it as "1439" and added a transcription of Cellarius's name.] Second inscription: Sum ex libris Danielis Comitis Vitoduranj Anno 1634. Nunc vero Heinrici Pavanij ibidem. 1663 [Ownership inscription of Daniel Graf, followed by ownership inscription of Heinricus Pavanius, both of Winterthur, Switzerland. The Graf family, like the Pfau family, were heavily involved in the pottery industry at Winterthur. Cf. The Grove Encyclopedia of Decorative Arts, ed. G. Campbell (Oxford: Oxford UP, 2006), v. 2, p. 558.] Penn Libraries call number: GC5 C4534 542d All images from this book Penn Libraries catalog record
photo.title: Ownership inscriptions of Joannes Kaufmannus, Daniel Graf, and Heinricus Pavanius (Winterthur, Switzerland)
